"Kassomenos P.A., McGregor G.R.","The interannual variability and trend of precipitable water over southern Greece",2006,"Journal of Hydrometeorology","7","2",,"271","284",,,10.1175/JHM484.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646587401&partnerID=40&md5=ddec1cc2077c94fa898a9dd37bbaf4f8","Laboratory of Meteorology, Department of Physics, University of Ioannina, P.O. Box 1186, 45110 Ioannina, Greece; Department of Geography, King's College London, London, United Kingdom","Kassomenos, P.A., Laboratory of Meteorology, Department of Physics, University of Ioannina, P.O. Box 1186, 45110 Ioannina, Greece; McGregor, G.R., Department of Geography, King's College London, London, United Kingdom","The precipitable water (PW) content was estimated over southern Greece for three atmospheric layers, using 28-yr twice-daily radiosonde measurements of temperature, humidity, and atmospheric pressure. Precipitable water demonstrates considerable variation at the monthly and interannual time scales as well as statistically significant upward trends at the annual level and for June-August (JJA) and September-November (SON). The relationship between PW and surface climate was also found to vary by season and surface climate variable. Disaggregation of seasonal PW trends by synoptic type revealed that seasonal trends might be attributed to increases in moisture in a limited number of airmass types such that maritime air masses appear to be becoming moister while their continental counterparts are drying. Despite fundamental changes to the intrinsic PW properties of air masses for some synoptic categories, the significance of these for determining the overall trend in seasonal PW levels is related to their weighted contribution as determined by changing airmass frequency. Consequently, the climatological effects of a moistening or drying air mass may be offset by a declining frequency. It is also shown that increasing PW trends cannot be attributed unequivocally to airmass warming as significant increases in PW have occurred in conjunction with falling temperatures in some seasons and airmass types. Accordingly, factors other than the commonly assumed global-warming-related increase in atmospheric moisture via the link between temperature and saturation vapor pressure must be considered if the mechanisms responsible for PW trends over southern Greece are to be fully understood. © 2006 American Meteorological Society.",,"annual variation; precipitation (climatology); precipitation assessment; radiosonde; Eurasia; Europe; Greece; Southern Europe",,,,,,"Angell, J.K., Elliott, W.P., Smith, M.E., Tropospheric humidity variations at Brownville, Texas and Great Falls, Montana, 1958-80 (1984) J. Climate Appl. Meteor., 23, pp. 1286-1296; Bethoux, J.P., Gentili, B., Tailliez, D., Warming and freshwater budget change in the Mediterranean since the 1940s, their possible relation to the greenhouse effect (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett., 25, pp. 1023-1026; Bokoye, A.I., Royer, A., O'Neill, N.T., Cliche, P., McArthur, J.B., Teillet, P.M., Fedosejevs, G., Theriault, J.M., Multisensor analysis of integrated atmospheric water vapor over Canada and Alaska (2003) J. Geophys. Res., 108, p. 4480. , doi:10.1029/2002JD002721; Bony, S., Duvel, J.P., Influence of the vertical structure of the atmosphere on the seasonal-variation of precipitable water and greenhouse-effect (1994) J. Geophys. Res., 99 (D6), pp. 12963-12980; Casey, K.S., Cornillon, P., Global and regional sea surface temperature trends (2001) J. Climate, 14, pp. 3801-3818; Chang, H.D., Hwang, P.H., Wilheit, T.T., Chang, A.T.C., Staelin, D.H., Rosenkranz, P.W., Monthly distributions of precipitable water from the NIMBUS-7 SMMR DATA (1984) J. Geophys. Res., 89, pp. 5328-5334; Chen, G., A 10-yr climatology of oceanic water vapor derived from the TOPEX Microwave Radiometer (2004) J. Climate, 17, pp. 2541-2557; Chen, T.C., Tzeng, R.Y., Global-scale intraseasonal and annual variation of divergent water-va